ce:section.ce:para:
Metallic organic photosensitizer dye consists of center metal ions and ligands, each featuring at least one anchoring group. Notably, ruthenium complex dye is the most representative metallic organic photosensitizer in DSSCs, with fundamental variants like N3, N719, N749, and Z907, as shown in Fig. 7
                        . N3 and N719 are often used as standard structures, facilitating the derivation of other ruthenium complex photosensitizers through molecular engineering. This involves strategies such as extending ligand conjugation, introducing electron donor groups, and modifying ligand compositions. The N3-based DSSCs show a maximum PCE of about 6%, and the N719-based standard cell reaches a PCE of 8.47 %. N749, often used in conjunction with N719, broadens the spectral response range. The absorption thresholds for N719 and N749 are experimentally determined at 680 nm and 820 nm, respectively (Lee et al., 2010). Z907 dye was designed by replacing two carbonylate groups with two hydrophobic nonyl groups in one of the bidentate anchoring ligands of N3 dye (Wu, 2022). Therefore, the Z907 dye exhibits higher hydrophobicity than the N3 dye. In addition, some comprehensive reviews have emphasized the significance of ruthenium-based complex dyes in DSSCs. For example, Wu (2022) focused on the strategies and methods for changing the basic chemistry of ruthenium-based complex dyes to optimize photovoltaic performance, i.e., tuning the optical and electronic properties of ruthenium-based complex dyes by designing the molecular structure. Tomar et al. (2020) focused on the essential characteristics of DSSCs with ruthenium complex-based sensitizers, such as short-circuit current (I

                           sc
                        ), open-circuit voltage (V

                           oc
                        ), and fill factor (FF). Many studies have conducted significant contributions to studies of dye properties and the performance of DSSCs in molecular engineering.
